Brian Hurt wrote:

&gt; Potiential solution- provide a skeletal inner class which &quot;exports&quot; 
&gt; private functions, like:
&gt; 
&gt; public class example {
&gt;     private int foo(int x, int y);
&gt;     private boolean bar(double z);
&gt; 
&gt;     public class testprivates {
&gt;         public int testfoo(int x, int y) {
&gt;              return foo(x, y);
&gt;         }
&gt;         public boolean testbar(double z) {
&gt;              return bar(z);
&gt;         }
&gt;     }
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; This is definately a violation of design style, and arguably as 
&gt; unesthetic as the original solution if not worse.  But I think it works (I 
&gt; haven&#39;t tried it- YMMV).

I&#39;d say it&#39;s a violation of *principles*. It tests neither the public 
interface nor the private interface that we want tested, but rather an 
in-between throwaway interface. It&#39;s an extra layer of coding, clutter, 
and potential bugs (it&#39;s highly vulnerable to cut-and-paste coding 
errors, and might hide them for a while when direct testing would detect 
them).

Back to my idea of implicit requirements - i think it is an implicit 
requirement of unit testing that we test the real interface, not a 
proxy. Feel free to disagree, as i&#39;m often wrong.

